| location = [[Liverpool]], [[Merseyside]], England| gbgridref = SJ 346 905| area = | elevation = | formed = | founded = | built = 1872| built_for = [[Midland Railway]]| demolished = | rebuilt = | restored = 1995–96| restored_by = Ken Martin| architect = [[Culshaw and Sumners#Henry Sumners|Henry Sumners]]| architecture = | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = [[National Museums Liverpool]]| designation1 = Grade II| designation1_offname = | designation1_type = | designation1_criteria = | designation1_date = 14 March 1975| delisted1_date = | designation1_parent = | designation1_number = 1062567| designation1_free1name = | designation1_free1value = | designation1_free2name = | designation1_free2value = | designation1_free3name = | designation1_free3value = | designation2 = | designation2_offname = | designation2_type = | designation2_criteria = | designation2_date = | delisted2_date = | designation2_parent = | designation2_number = | designation2_free1name = | designation2_free1value = | designation2_free2name = | designation2_free2value = | designation2_free3name = | designation2_free3value = }}
[[File:Midland Goods sign.jpg|thumb]]
The '''National Conservation Centre''', formerly the '''Midland Railway Goods Warehouse''', is located in [[Liverpool]], [[Merseyside]], England.  It stands in a block surrounded by Victoria Street, Crosshall Street, Whitechapel, and Peter Street.  After it closed as a warehouse it was converted into a conservation centre for [[National Museums Liverpool]] in the 1990s.  Initially its exhibition area was open to the public, but this closed in 2010.  The centre is recorded in the [[National Heritage List for England]] as a designated Grade&nbsp;II [[Listed building#England and Wales|listed building]].

==History==

The warehouse was built as a depot for the storage of railway freight in 1872 for the [[Midland Railway]].  It was designed by the local architect [[Culshaw and Sumners#Henry Sumners|Henry Sumners]] of [[Culshaw and Sumners]].<ref name=sharp>{{Citation| last = Sharples| first = Joseph| author-link = | contribution = William Culshaw (1807–74) and Henry Sumners (1825–95): rebuilding Victorian Liverpool | editor-last = Webster | editor-first = Christopher | title = The Practice of Architecture: eight architects, 1830–1930 | series = Spire Studies in Architectural History | volume = 2 | page =  67| publisher = Spire Books | place = Reading | year = 2012 | isbn = 978-1-904965-35-0 }}</ref>  The building was extended along Peter Street in 1878 in a similar architectural style.<ref name=pev>{{Citation | last = Sharples | first = Joseph| author-link = | last2 = Pollard| first2 = Richard| author2-link = | publication-date = | date = | year = 2004| title = Liverpool| edition = | volume = | series = Pevsner Architectural Guides| publication-place = New Haven and London| place = | publisher = Yale University Press| pages = | page = 190| format = | id = | isbn = 0-300-10258-5| doi = | oclc = | url = | accessdate =}}</ref>  Between 1995 and 1996 it was converted by another local architect, Ken Martin, into the Conservation Centre for National Museums Liverpool.<ref name=pye>{{Citation | last = Pye| first = Ken| author-link = | publication-date = | date = | year = 2011| title = Discover Liverpool|  publication-place = Liverpool| publisher = Trinity Mirror Media| pages = | page = 89|  isbn = 978-1-906802-90-5}}</ref>  In addition to its conservation work, the centre had an exhibition area open to the public to demonstrate the techniques of conservation, which attracted 60,000&nbsp;visitors a year.  In September 2005 the centre closed for refurbishment, and re-opened in June 2006 as the National Conservation Centre.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.icon.org.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=226:news-desk&catid=1:news-desk&Itemid=15| title = National Conservation Centre| accessdate = 13 September 2012| publisher = [[Institute of Conservation]]}}</ref>  Because of government cuts in funding, the visitor centre closed in 2010,<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/mediacentre/displayrelease.aspx?id=917| | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121017033104/http://liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/mediacentre/displayrelease.aspx?id=917| archivedate = 17 October 2012 |title = Public access to Conservation Centre to close| accessdate = 29 August 2013 | publisher = [[National Museums Liverpool]]}}</ref> but conservation work continues in the building.<ref name=pye/><ref>{{Citation | publication-date = 10 December 2010| date = | year = | title = Liverpool conservation centre to close| edition = | volume = | series = |  publisher = [[BBC]]| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-merseyside-11969862| accessdate =13 September 2012}}</ref>

==Architecture==

The centre is constructed in red brick on a [[Rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] stone [[plinth]], with stone dressings and bands, and some decoration in blue brick.  The exterior of the building is expressed as three or four storeys, and around the top of the building is a [[cornice]] with [[Glossary of architecture#modillion|modillions]].  The [[hip roof|hipped roof]] is in [[slate]].<ref name=nhl/>  On each of the four sides are arched openings large enough to admit freight.<ref name=pev/>  The front on Crosshall Street is concave; it is in eight [[bay (architecture)|bays]], each bay consisting of a tall blind arch containing windows, two of which also have arched entrances.<ref name=sharp/><ref name=pev/><ref name=nhl/>  On the Victoria Street front are carved [[spandrel]]s containing shields and the names of stations of the Midland Railway.<ref name=nhl/>  In 1921 Charles Reilly, Professor of Architecture at the [[University of Liverpool]], was of the opinion that at the time it was "one of the best buildings in the town".<ref>{{Citation | last = Reilly | first = Charles | author-link = Charles Herbert Reilly|  publication-date = | date = | year = 1921| title = Some Liverpool Streets and Buildings in 1921| publisher = [[Liverpool Daily Post|Liverpool Daily Post and Mercury]] |  page = 28| oclc = 504795181}}</ref>  On 14&nbsp;March 1975, it was designated as a Grade&nbsp;II listed building.<ref name=nhl>{{NHLE |num= 1062567|desc= Midland Railway Goods offices|accessdate=13 September 2012|mode=cs2|ps=none}}</ref>

